commText: Abdul Samad messed up final over chases against MI and KKR this season, but the management backed him and today he won them up a pretty improbable looking game. Sandeep Sharma was the hero for RR in their game against CSK when Dhoni was going berserk, but today he’ll feel the burden of letting his team down just because he couldn’t still inside the lines… Sport is such a great leveler in life!!

B0$ It was a situation where it was going to go one of two ways. Happy to get out on top of this one. We are all here to do our job, this is what the team needed today. Fantastic for it to pay off, and I had so much fun today out there. (On his dismissal) That was the ball I should have hit the most, I was disappointed the actual slot ball didn't go over the fence. I felt I left a lot out there with 17 needed off the final over, but then Samad did what he did and obviously we got that little bit of luck with the no ball.

formatValue: Glenn Phillips | Player of the Match:

commText: B0$ Emotions turned quite quickly, nice for us to get over the line. Chasing 215 isn't easy, and guys contributed all along to chase a big target. We knew in a quick outfield like this we'll score more than expected, but we had to be aggressive. Abhishek started up off, and then Tripathi gave him company. Then those cameos from Phillips and Klaasy. (On Samad's finishing skills) I think you got to train it, and put yourself under pressure. You are playing high risk cricket, so that's where technique comes in.

B0$ (Asked if they were happy with the total they got as the batting clicked as a unit) But with the target we posted, you can only feel happy once you win the game right, so not at all happy at the moment. (Asked if they should have scored more) That's a great question... I don't know. (Thoughts moving forward in the tournament) To be honest life is never easy playing this format, especially this tournament. Each and every game we have to play our best standard of cricket. We will come back and try to do it again.

B0$: This is what IPL gives you, matches like these makes the IPL special. You can never, never, never feel like you have won the game. I knew any opponent can win it and they were batting well too, but I was confident with Sandeep (defending the final over). He has won us a game from a similar situation (against CSK). He did it again today but that no-ball ruined our result. We played really well with the bat to put up that kind of a score on this wicket, but I think they (SRH) batted really sensibly, credit has to go to them for the way they batted. (About how he felt after the last ball was called a no-ball) Nothing much, it's a no ball, just have to bowl it again as simple as that, you don't think about it too much. Sandeep knows what to do. Maybe there might be a small change in mindset for a few seconds when you feel that the job is done, everyone was celebrating but I think that's the nature of this game, you can't step the line at that point of time.

B0$ It wasn't too long ago that Rajasthan Royals were riding high at the top of the table looking like the team to beat. But with just one win in the last five matches, their campaign is in danger of going off the rails. Their latest defeat, at the hands of table-toppers Gujarat Titans, was a real low point and they will be desperate to bounce back quickly. Speaking of low points, Sunrisers have had plenty of them this season and are in a situation where every game is a must-win contest if they are to dream of making the playoffs. So it's two teams who need a win very badly today. Hello and welcome to our live coverage of Match 52.

The buzzword at the post-match press conference after Friday's humiliation for Rajasthan Royals was intent. Kumar Sangakkara admitted that being thoroughly outclassed by Gujarat Titans was embarrassing and rued the absence of batting intent and their inability to consolidate on a solid start. 
 
That's been a recurring theme for this side as they've lost the most number of wickets between overs 7 and 15 (32) for all the teams this season, and have scored at a run rate of 7.82 in that period. Jos Buttler's dwindling form in the second half of the season have made the batting trouble through the middle even worse, and led to results like the one on Friday. 
 
Sangakkara preferred to write off the bad result against the holders and expects the side to get back on course. The extent to which RR's season has gone pear-shaped can be gauged from this damning fact - they've won as many games in the last five outings (one) as their opponents for Sunday, who are languishing at the ninth spot. Sunday presents them the best opportunity and opposition to repair the recent damage and remain relevant in the race for the playoffs. 
 
For SRH this season, expectation and reality have not even shared the same post code. At the auction this year, SRH made a squad with a bunch of exceptional T20 individuals, but more than a month into the season, they remain just that - a collection of individuals, failing to progress as a cohesive unit. 
 
Harry Brook's batting issues magnified SRH's struggles this year. The Englishman arrived with a massive ball-striking reputation and as a big-money signing (INR 13.25 Cr) but has struggled largely to adapt - 100* in one innings and a collective 63 in 8 others. Aiden Markram however, appeared to suggest on Saturday that he will be persisted with. Even in a season where just four points separates the team at the top (Gujarat Titans) and the team at seventh (Punjab Kings), SRH are still a few paces behind in the multi-team sprint to a top-four finish.
